window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2009>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2009","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CENTRE OF GRAVITY AND STABILITY~~SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"(i) You have been provided with two metre rules and other necessary apparatus  (ii) Place one of the rules on a knife edge and determine its centre of gravity C. Mark this position with a piece of chalk  (iii) Read and record the mass MR of the metre rule written in the reverse side of it  (iv) Attach the mass M = 100 g firmly to the rule AB at C using sellotape  (v) Suspend the metre rule by two parallel threads of length h = 40 cm each at the 10 cm and 90 cm marks. Ensure that the graduated face of the metre rule is facing upwards  (vi) Set the rule AB into a small angular oscillation about the vertical axis through its centre of gravity  (vii) Determine the time t for 20 oscillations. Evaluate the period T and T2  (viii) Read and record the value of d in metres  (ix) Keeping d constant throughout the experiment, repeat the procedure for other values of h = 50, 60, 70 and 80 cm. In each case determine the corresponding values of t, T, T2. Tabulate your readings  (x) Plot a graph T2 on the vertical axis against h on the horizontal axis  (xi) Determine the slope, s, of the graph. Evaluate k = sQ\\frac{s}{Q}Qs\u200b; where Q = 225d2\\frac{2}{25d^{2}}25d22\u200b  (xii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"(ii) C = 50.0 cm  (iii) MR = 150 g  (iv) M = 100 g  (v) No of oscillation, n = 20    S/Nh(cm)t1(s)t2(s)t = t1+t22\\frac{t_{1}+t_{2}}{2}2t1\u200b+t2\u200b\u200b(s)T = tn\\frac{t}{n}nt\u200b(s)T2(s2)140.027.0027.0027.001.351.82250.029.0029.0029.001.452.10360.032.0032.0032.001.602.56470.035.0035.0035.001.753.06580.037.0037.0037.001.853.42    (viii) d = 80.0cm        (xi) s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 3.4\u22121.980\u221242.5\\frac{3.4-1.9}{80-42.5}80\u221242.53.4\u22121.9\u200b = 125\\frac{1}{25}251\u200b = 0.04  Q = 225d2\\frac{2}{25d^{2}}25d22\u200b = 225\u00d7802\\frac{2}{25\u00d780^{2}}25\u00d78022\u200b = 0.000025  k = 0.042.5E\u221205\\frac{0.04}{2.5E-05}2.5E\u2212050.04\u200b = 3200    (xi)  Precautions:   1. I ensured that parallax error was minimized while reading the meter rule by positioning my eye directly in line with the measurement scale, allowing for accurate and precise readings.    2. I verified that the meter rule was balanced horizontally in each instance before taking measurements to ensure stability and accuracy, as any tilt could affect the oscillation and lead to erroneous results.    3. I checked that the support for the meter rule was firm and stable to prevent any unwanted movement during oscillation, which could compromise the reliability of the readings.    4. I conducted the experiment in a draft-free environment to minimize the effects of air resistance and fluctuations on the oscillation, ensuring that the measurements accurately reflected the true behavior of the meter rule during the experiment.    5. I took multiple measurements at different positions along the meter rule to ensure consistency in the oscillation results and to account for any potential variations.","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2009>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2009","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : PRINCIPLE OF MOMENTS~~SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION (S.H.M)","question":"Define the term couple as it relates to rotational or oscillatory systems.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"A couple in the context of rotational or oscillatory systems refers to a pair of equal and opposite forces acting on an object, where the forces do not act along the same line. This results in a rotational effect or torque without causing any translational motion. The moment of a couple is calculated by multiplying the magnitude of one of the forces by the perpendicular distance between the lines of action of the two forces. A couple produces a rotational effect that can cause an object to spin about its center of mass, making it fundamental in the study of mechanics and dynamics.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2009>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2009","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : PRINCIPLE OF MOMENTS","question":"Give two practical applications of a couple in everyday life.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"1. Steering Mechanisms: In vehicles, the steering wheel exerts a couple on the steering system, allowing the driver to turn the wheels smoothly and effectively without causing any lateral movement of the steering wheel itself.    2. Door Handles: When you push down on a door handle, a couple is created. The forces applied by your hand on the handle and the hinge on the opposite side generate a rotational motion that opens the door.    3. Wrenches and Tools: When using a wrench to tighten or loosen a bolt, the force applied at the handle creates a couple that helps turn the bolt. The effectiveness of the wrench depends on the distance between the point of force application and the bolt.    4. Climbing Gear: In climbing, a harness is designed to distribute weight evenly. When a climber applies force to a carabiner, it creates a couple that helps secure the climber without shifting the load unevenly.    5. Bicycle Pedals: When pedaling a bicycle, the force exerted on the pedals creates a couple about the pedal axle, which effectively turns the crankset and propels the bike forward.    6. Rotary Tools: In power tools like drills and saws, a couple is generated when forces are applied to the tool handle, allowing for efficient rotation and cutting actions.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2009>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2009","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : EVAPORATION AND BOILING","question":"(i) You have been provided a measuring cylinder, two different tins labelled C and D, thermometer and other necessary materials  (ii) Use the measuring cylinder provided to measure 100 cm3 of water and pour it into the tin labelled C  (iii) Heat the water in the tin to almost boiling (90\u00b0C)  (iv) Remove the tin and place it on a cork or wooden stand  (v) Insert the thermometer into the tin and record the temperature of water every minute starting from 85\u00b0C until the temperature drops to 65\u00b0C  (vi) Repeat the experiment with the tin labelled D using exactly the same volume of water and temperature range. Tabulate your readings  (vii) On the same graph sheet and using the same axes and scales plot two graph of temperature on the vertical axis and time on the horizontal axis from the readings obtained using tins C and D  (viii) Label the graph appropriated as C and D to correspond with the tins used  (ix) From each graph read off the time taken to cool from 85\u00b0C to 65\u00b0C  (x) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/Nt(min)TC(\u00b0C)TD(\u00b0C)10.085.085.021.081.080.032.078.075.043.075.072.054.072.070.065.069.067.076.067.065.087.065.063.098.063.061.0109.061.060.01110.060.060.0        The time taken to cool from 85\u00b0C to 65\u00b0C from graph C is 7 mins  The time taken to cool from 85\u00b0C to 65\u00b0C from graph D is 5.5 mins    (x)  Precautions:   1. I minimized parallax error when taking measurements from the thermometer by positioning my eye directly level with the scale to ensure accurate readings of the temperature.    2. I ensured even distribution of heat by stirring the mixture thoroughly to promote uniform temperature throughout the water, facilitating an accurate assessment of the cooling rate in both tins labeled C and D.    3. I placed both tins in the same environmental conditions to eliminate any external factors that could affect the rate of cooling, such as drafts or differences in ambient temperature.    4. I monitored and recorded the temperature at regular intervals to capture accurate data on the cooling process, allowing for a precise comparison between the two tins.    5. I allowed sufficient time for the water to reach a stable initial temperature before starting the cooling measurements, ensuring that the data reflects the cooling process accurately.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2009>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2009","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : HEAT TRANSFER","question":"Explain how heat losses by radiation and convection are minimized in a vacuum flask.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"In a vacuum flask, heat loss by radiation is minimized through the silvering of the inner walls, which reflects thermal radiation back into the flask, preventing heat from escaping. Heat loss by convection is reduced by the vacuum between the double walls of the flask, as the absence of air eliminates the medium for convective heat transfer, effectively insulating the contents and maintaining their temperature for a longer period.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2009>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2009","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : EVAPORATION AND BOILING","question":"State four factors which affect the rate of evaporation of a liquid in an open container.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The rate of evaporation of a liquid in an open container is affected by several factors, including:    1. Temperature: Higher temperatures increase the kinetic energy of the molecules in the liquid, leading to a higher rate of evaporation as more molecules have sufficient energy to escape into the vapor phase.    2. Surface Area: A larger surface area allows more molecules to be exposed to the air, increasing the rate of evaporation. For example, spreading a liquid in a shallow dish will evaporate faster than in a tall, narrow container.    3. Air Movement: Increased air movement or wind enhances evaporation by removing the vapor molecules from the surface of the liquid, allowing more liquid molecules to escape.    4. Humidity: Lower humidity levels in the surrounding air increase the rate of evaporation, as the drier air can absorb more vapor, whereas high humidity slows down evaporation since the air is already saturated with moisture.    5. Pressure: Lower atmospheric pressure can increase the rate of evaporation, as it reduces the energy barrier for liquid molecules to escape into the vapor phase.    6. Nature of the Liquid: Different liquids have varying evaporation rates based on their molecular properties; for example, volatile liquids like acetone evaporate faster than less volatile liquids like water due to weaker intermolecular forces.    These factors work together to influence how quickly a liquid evaporates in an open container.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2009>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2009","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"(i) Connect the circuit as shown in the diagram above. PQ is a potentiometer wire 100 cm long and R is a standard resistor of 5 \u03a9.  (ii) With the jockey J not making contact with PQ, close the switch. Read and record the ammeter reading I. Open the switch.  (iii) Use the jockey to make contact with PQ at 20 cm mark such that PJ = L = 20 cm. Close the switch, read and record the value I of the ammeter. Evaluate L-1.   (iv) Repeat the procedure for other values of L = 35, 50, 65 and 80 cm. In each case determine the corresponding value of I and L-1. Tabulate your readings.  (v) Plot a graph of L-1 on the vertical axis an I on the horizontal axis starting both axes from the origin (0,0).  (vi) From the graph deduce the value of  Io of I when L-1 = 0.  (vii) Evaluate IoI\\frac{I_{o}}{I}IIo\u200b\u200b.  (viii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"I = 0.40A    S/NL(cm)I(A)L-1(cm-1)120.01.050.050235.00.950.028350.00.850.020465.00.700.015580.00.650.013        (vi) when L-1  = 0, Io = 0.53.    (vii) IoI\\frac{I_{o}}{I}IIo\u200b\u200b = 0.530.4\\frac{0.53}{0.4}0.40.53\u200b = 1.33 A    (viii)  Precautions:   1. I ensured that the circuit key was kept open when not in use to prevent unnecessary discharge of the battery, thus prolonging its lifespan and ensuring consistent performance during the experiment.    2. I avoided parallax error by positioning my eye directly in line with the measurement scale on the ammeter, ensuring accurate readings without any angular distortion.    3. I ensured that all electrical wires were tightly and securely connected to prevent any current fluctuations, which could affect the accuracy of measurements.    4. I regularly inspected the battery voltage to ensure it remained within the operational range, preventing fluctuations that could skew the results.    5. I ensured that all insulation on wires was intact to prevent accidental short circuits or safety hazards.    6. I took multiple readings for each measurement and calculated an average to minimize random errors and enhance the reliability of the data collected.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2009>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2009","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"Define the e.m.f of a battery.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The e.m.f. (electromotive force) of a battery is the total energy per unit charge supplied by the battery when no current flows through the circuit. It represents the maximum potential difference between the battery terminals and is responsible for driving electric charge around a complete circuit.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2009>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2009","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"A cell X of e.m.f 1.00 V is balance by a length of 40.0 cm on a potentiometer wire. Another cell Y is balanced by a length 60.0 cm on the same wire. Calculate the e.m.f of Y.    (Provide your answer with the appropriate unit e.g 123.123 N)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"EyEx\\frac{E_{y}}{E_{x}}Ex\u200bEy\u200b\u200b = LyLx\\frac{L_{y}}{L_{x}}Lx\u200bLy\u200b\u200b    Ey1\\frac{E_{y}}{1}1Ey\u200b\u200b = 6040\\frac{60}{40}4060\u200b    \u2234 Ey = 32\\frac{3}{2}23\u200b = 1.5 V","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];